"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126001","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-05-17","<p>Health is a devolved matter in Northern Ireland. Richard Pengelly, Permanent Secretary at the Department of Health, has asked that such detailed questions be sent to the department. I therefore request that the honourable Member contact Mr Pengelly directly. His email is: <a href="mailto:richard.pengelly@health-ni.gov.uk" target="_blank">richard.pengelly@health-ni.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","253572 ; 253573","2019-05-17T09:05:32.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126001/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126001/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-05-13","Obesity: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 28 March to Question 236379 on Obesity: Northern Ireland, what representations her Department has (a) received from and (b) made to the Northern Ireland Department of Health on the establishment of a bariatric obesity service; whether she has plans to undertake a public consultation on the potential merits of establishing that service; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","253574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126002","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-21","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance on ‘Oesophago-gastric cancer: assessment and management in adults’ (2018) cautions that while nutrition support can improve surgical outcomes, practice in this field varies nationally so its effectiveness has not been determined.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-21T10:53:13.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126002/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126002/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-13","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of medical nutrition on clinical outcomes for cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","253575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126003","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-16","<p>In accordance with the usual convention, legal advice is not disclosed outside of the Government. This ensures that the Government can obtain full and frank legal advice in confidence.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-05-16T10:50:04.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126003/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126003/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-13","Birds: Pest Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on which occasions he requested legal advice on the revocation of General Licences 04/05/06 in the last year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","253444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126004","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-05-21","<p>The hexavalent chromate compound used in paints for vehicle servicing was banned in January 2019 under the Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals regulations. Work had been ongoing since 2006 to remove paints containing hexavalent chromate compounds, and the Ministry of Defence implemented this ban for the remaining few uses when it came into force. Updated instructions were provided to personnel and any remaining paints were recalled for safe disposal.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2019-05-21T15:02:47.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126004/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126004/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-05-13","Armed Forces: Hexavalent Chromium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Herald article entitled MoD stops using toxic chromium paint on tanks published on 17 April 2019, (a) when and (b) by whom the decision was taken to discontinue the use of paints containing hexavalent chromium on military vehicles.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","253590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126005","Treasury","false","2019-05-15","<p>I have responded to the letter dated 11 April 2019 as the Minister responsible for the scheme. Discussions with the Trustees of the Scheme are ongoing about possible changes that would benefit all parties.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-05-15T16:09:31.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126005/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126005/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-13","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to respond to the open letter of 11 April 2019 on the Mineworkers' Pension Scheme ;and if he will meet with the signatories of that letter.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","253552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126006","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-21","<p>Article 130(4) of the Withdrawal Agreement provides for the relative stability keys for the allocation of fishing opportunities to be maintained during the implementation period. This provision is intended to ensure that the UK’s share of quota cannot be reduced and that the UK will continue to be able to invoke Hague Preference during the implementation period.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-05-21T12:06:08.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126006/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126006/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-13","Fisheries: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the EU Withdrawal Agreement enables the UK to invoke Hague Preference during the implementation period.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","253554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126007","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-05-16","<p>The earliest that the UK can leave without a deal is 31 October 2019. Our priority remains delivering the deal to ensure a smooth and orderly exit before this date. While we do not want to leave with no deal and Parliament has also voted against this outcome three times, it remains the legal default at the end of the extension period in the event a Withdrawal Agreement cannot be agreed. As a responsible government we’ve been preparing to minimise any disruption in the event of no deal for over two years and will continue to prepare for all Brexit scenarios.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","James Cleverly",,"2019-05-16T13:58:58.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126007/answer","Biography information for James Cleverly","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126007/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-05-13","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the UK is able to leave the EU without a deal before 31 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","253451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126008","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-16","<p>Smart Energy GB is responsible for the national consumer awareness campaign for smart meters in Great Britain. Smart Energy GB is an independent, not for profit organisation funded by energy suppliers. Details of Smart Energy GB’s budget can be found at: <a href="https://www.smartenergygb.org/en/about-us/essential-documents" target="_blank">https://www.smartenergygb.org/en/about-us/essential-documents</a>.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-16T13:38:31.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126008/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126008/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much the Government has spent on TV and radio advertising to promote smart meters.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","253634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126009","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-16","<p>The Data Communications Company (DCC) and energy suppliers have obligations to upgrade their systems and operate SMETS1 smart meters within the DCC’s national communications network by the end of 2020.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-16T13:38:38.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126009/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126009/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the extent to which the Data Communications Company will install upgraded communication software to SMETS1 smart meters by 2020.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","253635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126010","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-16","<p>The Government is committed to publishing a new Cost Benefit Analysis for the Smart Meter Implementation Programme this year.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-16T13:38:43.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126010/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126010/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of conducting a new cost-benefit analysis of the smart meter roll-out over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","253636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126011","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-05-16","<p>When an individual suffering from domestic abuse requests a split payment, we will make split payments available to them.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst DWP is not intending to introduce split payments by default, as a department we respond positively to requests for split payments, and can take other actions to support those experiencing abuse, such as making a managed payment of rent direct to landlords. We also ensure that claimants who disclose domestic abuse are signposted to specialist organisations for support. All work coaches undergo mandatory training regarding how to support vulnerable claimants, including recognising the signs of domestic abuse.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to work closely with the Scottish Government to establish the practicalities of delivering split payments in Scotland.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-05-16T13:42:04.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126011/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126011/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-05-13","Universal Credit: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2019 to Question 212664 on Universal Credit: Domestic Violence, what recent discussions her Department has had with the Scottish Government on the implementation of separate universal credit payments by default; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","253698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126012","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>Network Rail does not have a lineside tree felling programme, however Network Rail does have a statutory duty to ensure that the railways remain safe and reliable for the millions of people who use the network every day. In the last year, there were more than a thousand incidents where trees caused disruption to the network, which in some cases resulted in injuries among train drivers and members of the public.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T11:44:23.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126012/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126012/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Railways: Tree Felling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trees have been felled by Network Rail as part its lineside tree felling programme to date.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","253699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126013","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>Network Rail does not have a dedicated lineside tree felling programme.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T11:52:28.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126013/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126013/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Railways: Tree Felling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trees Network Rail plans to fell as part of its lineside tree felling programme up to the expected conclusion of that programme in 2024.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","253700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126014","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>Network Rail does not have a lineside tree felling programme. While Network Rail has carried out replanting, where appropriate, on individual projects, it does not hold central data on the number of trees replanted across its estate.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T12:01:41.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126014/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126014/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Railways: Tree Felling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trees Network Rail are planning to replant to replace the loss of biodiversity resulting from its lineside tree felling programme.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","253701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126015","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-16","<p>Government is actively supporting good quality flexible working, of which home working can be part, and the provision of co-working spaces.</p><p>We have set up, with the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development, the Flexible Working Taskforce to promote wider understanding and implementation of inclusive flexible work and working practices. In January this year the Taskforce published a business case, supporting guidance and its members committed to support and promote the “Happy to Talk Flexible Working” campaign.</p><p>We have committed to consult on a new duty on employers to consider when a job can be done flexibly, and make that clear when advertising.</p><p>We have also committed to review the statutory right to request flexible working in 2020 and have commissioned some of the surveys to gather data for that work.</p><p>Through the Local Enterprise Partnership we promote economic growth and jobs in local areas. In order to deliver this objective, some LEPs have supported the creation of co-working spaces alongside advice and other support for business start-ups. This is being done in a number of ways, including through Growth Hubs and innovation centres.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-16T13:38:13.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126015/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126015/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support increased (a) home and flexible working and (b) provision of co-working spaces.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","253477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126016","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>Network Rail’s lineside engineers and surveyors consider a range of factors as part of their routine assessment of lineside trees, and whether these are considered safety critical or not. In the last year, there were more than a thousand incidents where trees caused disruption to the network, which in some cases resulted in injuries among train drivers and members of the public. Factors include the condition of the trees themselves, any identifiable hazards to oncoming trains and the safety risks associated with leaves on the line. This is in accordance with Network Rail’s own standards for vegetation management, which is based on existing forestry and environmental legislation.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T12:22:45.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126016/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126016/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Railways: Tree Felling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessments Network Rail carry out to classify a lineside tree as safety critical.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","253702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126017","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-16","<p>We carried out an impact assessment in 2014 on the extension of the statutory right to request flexible working, estimating a total benefit (net present value) of £474.9 million. This figure incorporates monetised benefits relating to the extension of the right to request to all employees with 26 weeks continuous service and therefore does not take into account the flexible working among parents and carers that was already taking place prior to the extension.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing the 2014 extension of the right to request Flexible working to all eligible employees. The review will test the economic assumptions underpinning the cost-benefit analysis in the original impact assessment.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-16T13:38:20Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126017/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126017/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the contribution to the economy of home and flexible working.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","253478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126018","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>Network Rail has a statutory duty to ensure that the railways remain safe throughout the year, and are therefore expected to intervene to address imminent safety risks or hazards that present themselves at the lineside, whenever this may be the case. As part of fulfilling this duty, Network Rail work with independent ecologists and arborists to identify nesting birds and protected species before commissioning any devegetation work, so that appropriate mitigation can be put in place to protect them and minimise disturbance.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T12:28:41.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126018/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126018/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Railways: Tree Felling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the independent review of Network Rail’s lineside vegetation management, published in November 2018, for what reasons Network Rail has felled trees during the nesting season.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","253703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126019","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-16","<p>A key economic objective of the planning system is to ensure that sufficient land of the right types is available in the right places to support growth and innovation. The revised National Planning Policy Framework, published in July last year, makes it clear that planning policies should allow for new and flexible working practices and be flexible enough to accommodate needs not anticipated in the plan.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-05-16T09:18:28.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126019/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126019/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-05-13","Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to use planning policy to support the provision of co-working spaces outside London.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","253479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126020","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-16","<p>The Department considers all aspects that may affect the rail and road network when assessing the changes of demand for the future.</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>The Department updated its rail forecasting guidance in 2016 to take into account different trip rates for people in different age groups and occupations. This was based on analysis of the National Travel Survey. The Department continues to review its forecasts, including analysing the impact of flexible working. The Departments’ guidance feeds into business cases for rail investments and franchise analysis. The guidance is called ‘WebTAG’ and is published on the Department’s website</p></li><li><p>The ‘Latest Evidence on Factors Impacting Road Traffic Growth’ review published by the Department in May 2018 included reviews of tele-commuting and the impact of e-commerce and social media on travel. The findings from this research informed the development of the Draft ‘Road Investment Strategy 2’.</p></li></ol>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-16T13:13:23.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126020/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126020/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the contribution of home and flexible working to reducing congestion on (a) rail and (b) road networks.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","253480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126021","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-16","<p>We work with a wide range of stakeholders across the tourism and hospitality sector across a range of issues, however this has not been raised with us. The provision of working spaces, or co-working spaces, is a business decision which is up to individuals to implement.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-05-16T09:23:09.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126021/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126021/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-05-13","Service Industries: Remote Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions his Department has had with the hospitality sector on supporting working spaces within hotels and cafes.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","253481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126022","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-21","<p>The Government wants patients to be able to benefit from access to effective new treatments as quickly as possible.</p><p>Through its technology appraisal and highly specialised technologies guidance, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) makes authoritative, evidence-based recommendations on whether medicines and other treatments represent a clinically and cost effective use of National Health Service resources. NHS organisations are legally required to make funding available for NICE recommended treatments, usually within three months of final guidance.</p><p>Wherever possible, NICE currently aims to publish recommendations on new drugs as soon as possible after licensing, with draft guidance on cancer drugs published in advance of licensing. The 2019 Voluntary Scheme for Branded Medicines Pricing and Access includes a commitment to faster NICE assessments of new medicines, with timelines for non-cancer drugs to match those for cancer drugs, subject to the evidence base for the product being sufficiently developed.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-21T10:58:38.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126022/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126022/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-13","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will expedite the process by which the NICE publishes its decisions.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","253483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126023","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-05-21","<p>The requested information can be found below:</p><p>A) Personal Independence Payment (PIP)</p><p>Statistics on Mandatory Reconsideration (MR) clearance times for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims by parliamentary constituency are planned to be published on 11th June 2019 in accordance with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The figures requested will be included within the PIP Official Statistics publication.</p><p>It should be noted that the Department’s decision makers are, in relation to PIP, now proactively engaging with claimants at the MR stage to ensure that they have all material evidence before they make their decision. Early indications are that this is helping decision makers.</p><p>B) Employment Support Allowance (ESA)</p><p>The available information on the average waiting time for MRs of ESA work capability assessments is published and can be found in table 16 here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/esa-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessments-including-mandatory-reconsiderations-and-appeals-march-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/esa-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessments-including-mandatory-reconsiderations-and-appeals-march-2019</a></p><p>It is the intention to produce further geographical breakdowns of these statistics in the future.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-05-21T14:41:04.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126023/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126023/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-05-13","Social Security Benefits: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average wait is for mandatory reconsideration of (a) personal independence payment and (b) employment support allowance claims in each of the last three years in Wrexham constituency.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","253531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126024","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-20","<p>Analysis of green belt land within half a mile of train stations, not including national parks, Areas Of Natural Beauty and Sites of Special Scientific Interest, was produced using publicly available datasets; it showed that there were just over 57,100 hectares of such land in England. However, the analysis does not indicate how much of this land is suitable for housing developments, or how much of that land is currently in use.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","253472","2019-05-20T14:45:10.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126024/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126024/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-05-13","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what analysis his Department has undertaken to identify green belt land close to train stations.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","253471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126025","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-20","<p>Analysis of green belt land within half a mile of train stations, not including national parks, Areas Of Natural Beauty and Sites of Special Scientific Interest, was produced using publicly available datasets; it showed that there were just over 57,100 hectares of such land in England. However, the analysis does not indicate how much of this land is suitable for housing developments, or how much of that land is currently in use.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","253471","2019-05-20T14:45:10.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126025/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126025/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-05-13","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what analysis his Department has undertaken to identify green belt land close to train stations and within an hour's travel time of London.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","253472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126026","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>The government is committed to reducing the adverse environmental impacts of transport. Reducing plastic and non-recyclable waste on public transport is predominantly a matter for transport operators. However, the Department for Transport (DfT) encourages improvements. For example, DfT sets targets in rail franchise agreements for operators to reduce waste to landfill and to increase the proportion of waste that is recycled.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail (NR) has installed drinking facilities in nine stations to reduce plastic waste and plans to introduce facilities to all other NR-managed stations. By the end of 2020, NR plans to ban retailers from supplying plastic cutlery and cups, implement a coffee cup recycling scheme, and expand the roll-out of coffee ground recycling to all NR-managed stations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-21T11:38:34.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126026/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126026/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Public Transport: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce (a) disposable and (b) non-recyclable waste on public transport services.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","253704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126027","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-21","<p>The majority of airlines are privately owned and the responsibility of disposable and non-recyclable waste reduction on services arriving to and departing from the UK is a matter for the companies concerned.</p><p>The Government has adopted a target of zero avoidable plastic waste by the end of 2042. The Aviation Strategy consultation paper highlights examples of best practice in waste reduction. As the Department continue to develop this strategy, it will be working with the aviation industry to help set out ambitions and share best practice to reduce levels of plastic waste produced by the sector still further, in order to ensure that the Government is able to achieve its 2042 goal.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-05-21T10:43:06.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126027/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126027/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-13","Aviation: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce (a) disposable and (b) non-recyclable waste on aviation services arriving to or departing from the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","253705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126028","Home Office","false","2019-05-20","<p>Under Common Travel Area arrangements Irish citizens have the right to enter and live in the UK without requiring permission. The same right is enjoyed by British citizens in Ireland.</p><p>Those who were born in the Republic of Ireland before 1949 are able to opt for British subject status, which then enables them to register as a British citizen if they wish to do so, based on a period of residence in the United Kingdom. If a person wishes to become a British citizen rather than a British subject, they must make such an application and pay the required fee.</p><p>Irish nationals born after 1949 can become British citizens by naturalisation. Irish nationals are regarded as settled in the UK and so are able to apply for citizenship after 5 years residence in the UK (3 years if the spouse or civil partner of a British citizen). This is a quicker route to citizenship than for other nationals. There are currently no plans to make an assessment of applications for citizenship without a fee.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-05-20T10:34:36.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126028/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126028/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-05-13","British Nationality: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of extending the right to apply for UK citizenship without a fee to people born in the Republic of Ireland and who have lived in the UK for most of their life.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","253726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126029","Treasury","false","2019-05-16","<p>The sale of food that is formulated and held out for sale exclusively for working dogs, which includes assistance and therapy dogs, is zero rated. The VAT rules in this area are long-standing and have not changed.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-05-16T13:30:33.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126029/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126029/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-13","Assistance Animals: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons VAT will be charged on food for assistance and therapy dogs.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","253520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126030","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-16","<p>Public Health England (PHE) ensures health professionals have current, accurate information on the benefits of immunisation, so they can communicate this information to parents. PHE provides the Department with expert evidence and advice (and nationally procures many vaccines). PHE also supports NHS England with information, expert advice, capacity and support at national and local level.</p><p>PHE recommends people visit the National Health Service website as the NHS is a highly trusted source of information. This is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vaccinations/" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vaccinations/</a></p><p>There are also a range of information leaflets, available online and from health professionals, about the different vaccination programmes at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immunisation#immunisation-leaflets-and-guidance-for-parents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immunisation#immunisation-leaflets-and-guidance-for-parents</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-16T15:46:15.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126030/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126030/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-13","Vaccination: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that parents are given adequate advice and information on vaccination programmes.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","253521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126031","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-16","<p>The Government’s mandate to NHS England requires NHS England to deliver the actions set out in the Challenge on Dementia 2020 Implementation Plan. The Implementation Plan envisages that:</p><p>“In every part of the country people with dementia having equal access to diagnosis as for other conditions, with an expectation that the national average for an initial assessment should be 6 weeks following a referral from a GP (where clinically appropriate), and that no one should be waiting several months for an initial assessment of dementia.”</p><p>We have made great strides in delivering the Challenge: this includes being above NHS England’s target for two thirds of people living with dementia to receive a formal diagnosis. Our focus now is on reducing the variation of local diagnosis rates and NHS England have programmes in place to further improve the quality and timeliness of diagnosis.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-05-16T11:37:23.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126031/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126031/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-13","Dementia: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that (a) dementia and (b) Alzheimer’s are diagnosed (i) correctly and (ii) as quickly as possible.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","253522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126032","Treasury","false","2019-05-16"," The Government is committed to public service pensions which are fair to workers and fair to other taxpayers. The tapered annual allowance is focussed on the highest earning pension savers, to ensure that the benefit they receive is not disproportionate. The Government is aware of specific concerns raised by some high-earners impacted by annual allowance tax charges. All public sector pay and pensions policies are kept under constant review and discussed with relevant departments.","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-05-16T13:19:35.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126032/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126032/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-13","Doctors: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care and the Secretary of State for Defence on the annual tapered allowance and its effect on the recruitment and retention of doctors in the NHS and armed forces.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","253507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126033","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-20","<p>Payments made under section 4 of the Ministerial and other Pensions and Salaries Act 1991 for 2016-17 and 2017-18 are published in the Department’s annual report and accounts, see page 88: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/beis-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">BEIS Annual Report and Accounts 2016 to 2017 GOV.UK</a> and page 87: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/725808/BEIS_Web_accessible_Annual_Report_and_Accounts_2017_18.pdf" target="_blank">BEIS Annual Report and Accounts 2017 to 2018 GOV.UK</a>. Figures for 2018-19 will be included in the 2018-19 Annual Report and Accounts to be published later this year.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson",,"2019-05-20T16:07:10.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126033/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126033/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Former Ministers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has paid to hon. Members under section 4 of the Ministerial and other Pensions and Salaries Act 1991 since 13 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","253603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126034","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-20","<p>Any such payments are published in the department’s audited annual accounts, which can be found on gov.uk.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-05-20T13:45:18.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126034/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1126034/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-05-13","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Former Ministers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department has paid to hon. Members under section 4 of the Ministerial and other Pensions and Salaries Act 1991 since 13 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","253604"
